	<div class="container">
	<!-- page content goes inside the container -->

		<h1>Grace's Potato Chip Cookies </h1>

		<p class="intro">
			A recipe for potato chip cookies that my great aunt Grace makes for Christmas. 
        	<br>
        <em>Makes about 40 cookies.</em></p>
     

		<ul>
			<li>1 cup (2 sticks) unsalted butter <em>at room temperature</em></li>
            <li>2 cups flour</li>
			<li>1 cup sugar</li>
			<li>1 teaspoon vanilla extract</li>
            <li>1/4 tsp salt</li>
            <li>1/2 cup pecans <em>chopped</em></li>
            <li>1/2 cup potato chips <em>crushed</em></li>
                           
		</ul>
        <p>Chocolate Dip Finish (optional)</p>
        <ul>
            <li>4 ounces semi-sweet or bitterweet chocolate <em>finely chopped</em></li>
            <li>1 tsp butter, canola oil or vegetable shortening</li>
            
        </ol>
        
        <h3>Instructions</h3>
       
            <p>Preheat your oven to <strong>350</strong> degrees F. Line two baking sheets with parchment paper and set aside. In a large bowl, mix together the <strong>butter</strong> with <em>1/2 cup</em> of the <strong>sugar</strong> until lightly and fluffy. Next, mix in the <strong>vanilla</strong> and <strong>salt</strong> until smooth. Add the <strong>pecans</strong>, crushed <strong>potato chips</strong> and <strong>flour</strong> together and mix until just combined. </p>

<p>Place the remaining <em>1/2 cup</em> <strong>sugar</strong> in a small bowl. Scoop a tablespoon-sized mound of dough and form it into a small ball with the palms of your hands. Roll the ball in the remaining sugar until coated. Place cookies on baking sheet, about <strong>1 inch apart.</strong></p>

<p>Bake cookies until lightly golden at the edges, about <strong>15 minutes</strong>. Transfer to cool on a wire rack.</p>

<p>If dipping in chocolate, melt chocolate with butter, oil or shortening in a double boiler or in short bursts in the microwave. Stir until smooth. Dip half of each fully cooled cookie in the chocolate, and let dry and harden on a wire rack.</p>
        
        
        
       


